<gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF042647%2F1"><gtr:id>AC4A3AC6-3B32-43EF-81E3-FFD2B125DE94</gtr:id><gtr:title>Contesting land tenure reform in South Africa: policy-making processes and legal spaces</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F042647/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>This ESRC Postdoctoral Fellowship (PDF) supports research that engages directly with real change affecting millions of people living in the former ?homelands? of South Africa.&amp;nbsp; These areas cover just 13 per cent of the country but are home to more than 15 million people (more than a third of the population), 73 per cent of them living in poverty.&amp;nbsp; The Communal Land Rights Act (CLARA) was passed unanimously by Parliament in 2004 to reform land tenure in these areas.&amp;nbsp; However, these reforms were controversial and subsequently a constitutional challenge has been brought against the government in relation to CLARA.&amp;nbsp; The doctoral research already undertaken by the Fellow considered how different groups became pitted against each other in the policy and law-making processes of CLARA: government bureaucrats, ANC politicians, traditional leaders in the former ?homelands?, human rights lawyers, land sector and gender activists.&amp;nbsp; The PDF will support the publication of the Fellow?s doctoral research on the controversy surrounding the Parliamentary processes and its dissemination in South Africa.&amp;nbsp; It will also support follow-up research analysing the conflict, as it moves to the contrasting legalised arena of the court hearings.&amp;nbsp; This will involve in-depth interviews with key participants in addition to attendance and observation of the hearings.
